'''Charles William Dalmon''' (-)<ref>Date of birth is in John Lane Co. records.[http://www.hrc.utexas.edu/research/fa/lane.john.corr.html]</ref> was a British poet, 1890s decadent, 1920s film designer<ref>Work with Lucky Cat Films in the early 1920s.[http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/862832/index.html]. Credits for art direction for a 1928 film ''The Blue Peter''[http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/26997?view=credit].</ref>, and friend of .<ref>Dalmon is supposed to have uttered the outrageous ''my ambition is to be crushed to death between the thighs of a guardsman.''[http://homepages.tesco.net/chatfieldmoore/dand.htm].</ref>
He was a contributor to '''', and was published in ''The Living Age'', in the mid-1890s. His poems subsequently appeared in many anthologies<ref>Including his ''Camelot'' in the 1929  ''Twentieth-Century Poetry''.</ref>, but his reputation was never bright.<ref>A '''' review [http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=/arts/2006/06/25/svbetjeman25.xml] (25 June 2006) noted that  was a fan, classing Dalmon with "dim and half-forgotten poets" such as ,  and .</ref> Jean Moorcroft Wilson<ref>In her ''Siegfried Sassoon'', volume II (1918-1967) from 2003, p.257.</ref> notes that  and  planned to publish "small, neglected authors", into which group Dalmon fell with  and . 
There are ascriptions to Dalmon of  songs and s, which may be collector's or editor's rather than author's credits. ''O what if the fowler my blackbird has taken?'' is given as by him[http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/fulltext/ms1896/index.htm], but there is a related old ballad.[http://www.nls.uk/broadsides/broadside.cfm/id/15836/transcript/1] ''The (Red) Fuchsia Tree'', set by [http://www.btinternet.com/~J.Benton/roger_quilterV1.htm] and [http://www.kcedensor.freeserve.co.uk/raynor/ray_cat.htm], is attributed to Dalmon but may be traditional.<ref> See the Preface[http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/fulltext/ms1896/apreface.htm] to the 1896 collection of arrangements ''Manx National Songs'', by W. H. Gill, for the context.</ref>
